:"Lanarkshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Wick, Caithness, Scotland":"Wick, Caithness, Scotland","Peebles, Peeblesshire, Scotland":"Peebles, Peeblesshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Stonehouse, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Stonehouse, Lanarkshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Mowat","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish (Caithness and Orkney): variant of   Mowatt  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Mowatt","meanings":["Scottish (northeastern): habitational name from Mold (Flintshire), see   Maude   1. The distinctive Scottish form of the name has arisen from a shift of stress in <i>Mohaut</i> from the second to the first syllable. In Caithness and Orkney, the surname is traditionally pronounced ‘Mode’."]}]},{"name":"George","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When George Mowat II was born in 1335, in Peebles, Peeblesshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, George Mowat I, was 17 and his mother, Christina Plowman, was 16. He married Elizabeth Doull in 1360, in Stonehouse, Lanarkshire, Scotland, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1378, in Lanarkshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 43, and was buried in Lanarkshire, Scotland, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1335–1378":"1335–1378","1340–1382":"1340–1382","1365–1435":"1365–1435","1318–Male":"1318–Surnud","1319–Female":"1319–Surnud","1435":"1435","1335":"1335","before 1335":"enne 1335","1378":"1378","1365":"1365","1340":"1340","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","24 November 1365":"24. november 1365","1319":"1319","1318":"1318","Carnwarth, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Lanarkshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Wick, Caithness, Scotland":"Wick, Caithness, Scotland","Peebles, Peeblesshire, Scotland":"Peebles, Peeblesshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Stonehouse, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Stonehouse, Lanarkshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"1335–1378":"1335–1378","1340–1382":"1340–1382","1365–1435":"1365–1435","1318–Male":"1318–Kuollut","1319–Female":"1319–Kuollut","1435":"1435","1335":"1335","before 1335":"ennen vuotta 1335","1378":"1378","1365":"1365","1340":"1340","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","24 November 1365":"24. marraskuuta 1365","1319":"1319","1318":"1318","Carnwarth, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Lanarkshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Wick, Caithness, Scotland":"Wick, Caithness, Scotland","Peebles, Peeblesshire, Scotland":"Peebles, Peeblesshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Stonehouse, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Stonehouse, Lanarkshire, Scotland"},"fr":{"1335–1378":"1335–1378","1340–1382":"1340–1382","1365–1435":"1365–1435","1318–Male":"1318–Décédé","1319–Female":"1319–Décédée","1435":"1435","1335":"1335","before 1335":"avant 1335","1378":"1378","1365":"1365","1340":"1340","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","24 November 1